    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-06-09T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-06-09T08:00:00-05:00" n="328"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3812: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-09T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 9, 1934—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 9—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>152. Consulate’s 149 June 9, 10 a.m. Yokoyama has just called on me to discuss’
                    Japan’s reply. He stated that he was fully cognizant of the Italian position
                    vis-à-vis the arms embargo and while he felt that “Japan’s reply” might be
                    agreeable to Italy he regretted that it might not give satisfaction to the
                    United States and Great Britain. He stated that the form and substance of
                    Japan’s reply were solely governed by Japan’s relations with the League.</p>
                <p>He then stated that should the United States or Great Britain care to approach
                    Tokyo direct in this matter he felt that a more satisfactory response might be
                    obtained.</p>
                <pb facs="0335" n="265" xml:id="pg_265"/>
                <p>It seemed entirely evident to me that he was acting under instructions.</p>
                <p>In view of the delicate character of this situation I am not saying anything
                    about this to the British. Please instruct.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
